<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Nicaragua's relationship with the United States in the 1920s was characterized by:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Complete independence from U.S. influence</option>
            <option letter="b">U.S. military occupation and financial control</option>
            <option letter="c">Equal diplomatic partnership</option>
            <option letter="d">Communist alliance</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>During the 1920s, Nicaragua was under significant U.S. control through military occupation and financial supervision. U.S. Marines were stationed there from 1912 to 1933, ostensibly to protect American interests and maintain stability. This intervention faced resistance from Nicaraguan nationalists, particularly Augusto Sandino, who led a guerrilla campaign against U.S. presence.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
